            <h2 class="reflection-title">A Philosophy of Constraint</h2>
            
            <p class="reflection-text">
                Humanist Modernism succeeded not despite its constraints, but because of them. By insisting that typography must be generous, that measures must be optimal, that shadows must be subtle, and that ornament must be eliminated, HM creates a design philosophy that is simultaneously more restrictive and more liberating than Bauhaus. More restrictive because every decision must serve the reader. More liberating because designers are freed from the burden of expressing personal vision through geometric complexity. The reader wins. The content wins. And paradoxically, the design itself—humble, warm, and invisible—becomes the most beautiful of all.
            </p>
        </div>
